[h1]Array Length[/h1]

You can access the length of an array (the number of elements it stores) via its [b]length[/b] property. 
[b]Example:[/b] [code format="java" codeId="747"]int[ ] intArr = new int[5];
System.out.println([b]intArr.length[/b]);

//Outputs 5[/code]

quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to calculate the sum of myArray's elements using the for loop, and print it to the screen. myArray is an array of doubles, containing 4 elements.
[!raw!]
double sum = 0.0;
for (int x = 0; x < 4; x{0}) {
 sum += myArray[x];
}
System.out.println({1});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Arrays[/h1]

Now that we know how to set and get array elements, we can calculate the sum of all elements in an array by using loops.
The [b]for [/b]loop is the most used loop when working with arrays, as we can use the [b]length [/b]of the array to determine how many times to run the loop. [code format="java" codeId="748"]int [ ] myArr = {6, 42, 3, 7};
int sum=0;
for(int x=0; x<myArr.length; x++) {
   sum += myArr[x];
}
System.out.println(sum);

// 58[/code]
In the code above, we declared a variable [b]sum [/b]to store the result and assigned it 0.
Then we used a [b]for [/b]loop to iterate through the array, and added each element's value to the variable.
[note]The condition of the [b]for [/b]loop is x<myArr.length, as the last element's index is [b]myArr.length-1[/b].[/note]
